<b><font size=+1>
List:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2">namedroppers</a>
Subject:    <a href="?t=95837887600005&r=1&w=2">3rd root server</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837661900004&r=1&w=2">Murray.pa () Xerox ! ARPA</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198506">1985-06-29 16:15:50</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426499&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426499&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

I suggest that we not bring up a 3rd server for a while. That will give
us all a chance to debug our down-server code. No matter how hard we try
to replicate things, there are going to be times when you can't contact
any of the servers. I've chased a few bugs out of my code during the
past week.

My code now remembers a list of questions that can't be answered because
the servers are down. This was a bit ugly because it rippled out to the
next layer. The mail server, for example, now has to process the
don't-know-yet answer from the name to address routine. This wasn't a
big deal because the existing code to process the server-not-responding
case does all the work.
	
PS: I thought of another thing that has to go on the list of common
failure modes to be avoided: planned downtime. I can just see it now.
It's 3AM on Sunday morning the week after 4.3 is released. The folks at
Purdue and Rice both decide it's a great time to bring up the new
software....

